<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1122,1759]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1517,1542]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Remarks.</emphasis>
In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Boucek" box="[475,655,1517,1542]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Boucek, Z. (1965 a) Studies of European Eulophidae, IV: Pediobius WALK. and two allied genera (Hymenoptera). Acta Entomologica Musei Nationalis Pragae, 36, 5 - 90." type="journal article" year="1965" yearSuffix="a">Bouček (1965a)</bibRefCitation>
to European species, the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Kamijo" box="[1024,1203,1517,1542]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Kamijo, K. (1986 a) A key to species of Japanese species of Pediobius (Hymenoptera, Eulophidae). The Entomological society of Japan, 54, 396 - 404." type="journal article" year="1986" yearSuffix="a">Kamijo (1986a)</bibRefCitation>
to Japanese species, and the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Peck" box="[335,475,1554,1579]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Peck, O. (1985) The taxonomy of the Nearctic species of Pediobius (Hymenoptera: Eulophidae), especially Canadian and Alaskan forms. The Canadian Entomologist, 117, 647 - 704. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.4039 / ent 117647 - 6" type="journal article" year="1985">Peck (1985)</bibRefCitation>
to Nearctic species of 
<taxonomicName box="[753,865,1554,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[753,865,1554,1579]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Pediobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[883,1047,1554,1579]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolapilus">
<emphasis box="[883,1047,1554,1579]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. petiolapilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
runs to 
<taxonomicName box="[1151,1287,1555,1578]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="termerus">
<emphasis box="[1151,1165,1555,1578]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1184,1287,1555,1578]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">termerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1286,1290,1555,1578]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">,</emphasis>
from which females differ in the following: interscrobal space weakly raised (
<figureCitation box="[958,1047,1589,1614]" captionStart="FIGURE 33" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1358,1380]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,738,1336]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[151,1436,738,1336]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 33. Pediobius spp., head in front view. a: Pediobius bisulcatus Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female; b: Pediobius elongatus Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female; c: Pediobius petiolapilus Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female; d: Pediobius prominentis Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female; e: Pediobius narangae Sheng &amp; Wang, 1994, female; f: Pediobius tortricida Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female; g: Pediobius saulius (Walker, 1839), female; h: Pediobius saulius (Walker, 1839), male. Scale bar: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375792/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
c) rather than sharply projected; frontofacial sutures extending to vertex and visible in dorsal view (
<figureCitation box="[923,992,1626,1651]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1030,1052]" captionTargetBox="[175,1436,193,1008]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1008]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pediobius petiolapilus Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female. a: body in dorsal view; b: body in lateral view; c: antenna; d: fore wing; e: fore leg; f: mid leg; g: hind leg. Scale bar: a – b, 0.5 mm; c, e – g, 0.2 mm; d: 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375762/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
a); scutellum strongly reticulate except smooth laterally and apically (
<figureCitation box="[492,558,1661,1686]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1030,1052]" captionTargetBox="[175,1436,193,1008]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1008]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 3. Pediobius petiolapilus Cao &amp; Zhu, sp. n., female. a: body in dorsal view; b: body in lateral view; c: antenna; d: fore wing; e: fore leg; f: mid leg; g: hind leg. Scale bar: a – b, 0.5 mm; c, e – g, 0.2 mm; d: 0.4 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375762/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
a); petiole with two setae instead of one on each side. Based on its similarities with 
<taxonomicName box="[208,336,1699,1722]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="termerus">
<emphasis box="[208,222,1699,1722]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[236,336,1699,1722]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">termerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, we include 
<taxonomicName box="[479,639,1698,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="petiolapilus">
<emphasis box="[479,639,1698,1723]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">P. petiolapilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName box="[716,801,1698,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Pediobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alcaeus">
<emphasis box="[716,801,1698,1723]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">alcaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group, which can be separated from the other species in this group by the combination of characters given in the key (couplet 4).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
